print("\n\n==================Headers below =====================")
my_headers = soup.find_all("h2")
for headers in my_headers:
    print(f"\n{headers}")

print("\n\n================== link below =====================")
# Find all the links on the page with an "href" attribute
my_links = soup.find_all("a", href=True)

# Print out the URLs of the links
for link in my_links:
    print(link['href'])


print("\n\n================== image below  =====================")
# Find all the images on the page
my_images = soup.find_all("img")

# Print out the URLs of the images
for image in my_images:
    src = image.get("src")
    if src:
        print(src)
    else:
        print("Image has no source attribute:", image)


print("---------------- Paragraph Below ------------------")
my_paragraph = soup.find_all("p")
for paragraph in my_paragraph:
    print(f"\n{paragraph}")

print("\n\n==================Item below =====================")
item = soup.find_all("div", {"class": "_flx _lpbwg"})
for item in item:
    print(f"\n{item}")

<p><p>Looking to buy a TV that suits your budget and needs? The Gadgets 360 TV Finder is here to help. From veteran TV makers like Sony and Samsung to relatively new players such as Nokia and Xiaomi, there are a plethora of brand and their offerings to browse and select from. Using the filters and tabs below, you can not only view all your favourite brands at once, but also tailor the search to meet your requirements. The tabs on top will help you sift through TVs based on price, popularity, day of launch, and name. The Latest tab will show you TVs that were launched recently, in a reverse chronological order. If you have a tight budget, click on the Low Price tab to check out pocket-friendly TV models. If you’re looking for something premium, simply click on the High Price tab to check out top-end TV sets. To check out which TV models are most popular among our readers, click on Popularity. If you have a specific TV in mind, you can easily look it up via the Search tab.</p>
<p>The Gadgets 360 TV Finder also comes in with a set of handy filters that you can play around with to find the TV that suits you best. Using the filters, found on the left, is really easy, too. Start by setting a suitable price bracket from the Price Range filter, followed by selecting the brand(s) of your choice from the Brand filter. Looking for a huge screen? Select the 65-inch and Larger option from the Screen Size filter. Wish to browse something smaller? Simply select the required size from the same filter. Note that you can select multiple options on any filter, so we encourage you to click on multiple options of your choice to find the TV that suits you best. The Resolution Standard filter will help you choose the right option, starting from HD-Ready and going all the way up to 8K. If you know exactly which pixel resolution you wish to go for, go ahead and select the right option(s) on the Resolution (Pixels) filter. Can’t decide between OLED or Plasma? Why not select both option on Screen Type filter and check out the TVs that come up?</p>
<p>This is the age of smart TVs and the RAM, Storage, and Number of Processor Cores will help you find just the right hardware muscle you are looking for in your next new TV set. If all that sounds too technical, you can simply click on the Smart TV option from the More Features filter below. The More Features filter will also show you several handy features to choose from, ranging from finding a TV with a headphone jack, or one that supports Wi-Fi for connectivity. If you are looking at serious competitive gaming on your TV, you may wish to go for a model with a higher refresh rate, from the Refresh Rate filter. If you’re looking for gorgeous visuals, you can select the option from your choice from the HDR filter. In [10]:
def plot1():
    brand_count = {}
    names = df['name']
    for nam in names:
        if nam in brand_count:
            brand_count[nam] += 1
        else:
            brand_count[nam] = 1

    # Plot the bar graph
    plt.bar(range(len(brand_count)), list(brand_count.values()), align='center')
    plt.xticks(range(len(brand_count)), list(brand_count.keys()), rotation=90)
    plt.xlabel('TV Brands')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title('TV Brands and their Count')
    plt.show()


plot1()

Based on the plots provided, here are some potential recommendations:

Bar chart: The bar chart shows the count of each TV brand in the dataset. From this chart, you can see which brands are most popular and which are less common. This information could be useful for marketing and advertising purposes, as well as for understanding the competitive landscape of the TV market.

Scatter plot: The scatter plot shows the relationship between TV price and display size. From this chart, you can see that there is a positive correlation between these two variables - as display size increases, so does the price of the TV. This information could be useful for pricing decisions, as well as for understanding customer preferences and willingness to pay for larger screens.

Pie chart: The pie chart shows the distribution of TV screen types in the dataset. From this chart, you can see that the majority of TVs in the dataset are LED, followed by OLED and QLED. This information could be useful for understanding market trends and for making decisions about which types of screens to prioritize in product development.

Line chart: The line chart shows the relationship between TV price and display size, with each point representing a different TV model. From this chart, you can see that there is some variation in the price of TVs with the same display size, suggesting that factors other than display size (such as brand, features, or technology) may be driving differences in price. This information could be useful for pricing decisions and for understanding the competitive landscape of the TV market.

Overall, the plots suggest that display size is an important factor in determining the price of a TV, but that there are other factors (such as brand, features, and technology) that also play a role. The data also suggests that LED screens are the most common type of screen in the dataset, and that there is a wide range of TV brands represented. These insights could be useful for companies in the TV industry looking to make strategic decisions about product development, marketing, and pricing.
